  "prompt": "How often do a Tesla's batteries need to be replaced?",
  "response": "Tesla batteries are designed to last a long time, typically well within the lifespan of the vehicle itself. Most Tesla vehicles are covered by an 8-year warranty, which varies slightly depending on the model. Generally, Tesla batteries are engineered to deliver at least 70-80% of their original capacity over these 8 years or roughly 100,000 to 150,000 miles. Real-world data from Tesla owners has shown that the battery degradation is often minimal over this period. Therefore, in most cases, a Tesla's battery does not need replacement within the typical lifespan of the vehicle unless there is a significant fault.\n\nHowever, battery longevity can be affected by various factors including driving habits, climate, charging habits, and more. With regular use and optimal charging practices, a Tesla battery could potentially last even longer, delaying the need for replacement significantly.",
